2. DaemonSet for Node Exporter
A minimal DaemonSet specification might look like:

yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: custom-node-exporter
  namespace: my-user-monitoring
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: custom-node-exporter
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: custom-node-exporter
    spec:
      hostNetwork: true
      tolerations:
        - key: node-role.kubernetes.io/master
          operator: Exists
          effect: NoSchedule
      containers:
        - name: node-exporter
          image: quay.io/prometheus/node-exporter:latest
          ports:
            - containerPort: 9100
          securityContext:
            privileged: true  # needed to read host-level metrics
      # If your cluster requires a SecurityContextConstraints (SCC) change,
      # you may need to grant this DS permission to run privileged pods.
Notes:

Privileged: Node Exporter typically requires privileged access to read host filesystems, CPU info, etc.

hostNetwork: So it can bind to :9100 for each node.

You might need an appropriate SCC or cluster-role binding if the default policies do not allow privileged DaemonSets in that namespace.

3. Service & ServiceMonitor
Service:

yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: custom-node-exporter-service
  namespace: my-user-monitoring
  labels:
    app: custom-node-exporter
spec:
  ports:
    - name: metrics
      port: 9100
      targetPort: 9100
  selector:
    app: custom-node-exporter
ServiceMonitor (so your user-workload Prometheus can discover & scrape it):

yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: monitoring.coreos.com/v1
kind: ServiceMonitor
metadata:
  name: custom-node-exporter-sm
  namespace: my-user-monitoring
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: custom-node-exporter
  endpoints:
    - port: metrics
      interval: 30s
  namespaceSelector:
    matchNames:
      - my-user-monitoring
Key Points:

The selector under spec.selector.matchLabels must match the labels on the Service (and in turn, the DaemonSet pods).

The user-workload Prometheus typically scrapes any ServiceMonitor in any user namespace (unless restricted). If you place it in the same namespace as the DaemonSet, everything is straightforward.

4. Remote Write to Central Cluster
Once user-workload Prometheus is scraping the custom Node Exporter, you can remote write those metrics to your central Prometheus (or Observability cluster) by adding a remoteWrite: section to the user-workload-monitoring-config in openshift-user-workload-monitoring. For example:

yaml
Copy
Edit
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: user-workload-monitoring-config
  namespace: openshift-user-workload-monitoring
data:
  config.yaml: |
    prometheus:
      remoteWrite:
        - url: "https://central-prom.example.com/api/v1/write"
          bearer_token: "mySecret"
